### Zod 3 Transform Method Usage

Source: https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/blob/main/packages/docs-v3/MIGRATION.md

This snippet demonstrates the updated and simplified transformer syntax in Zod 3. The `.transform()` method can now be directly applied to any Zod schema, taking a single function that performs the transformation. This change streamlines the process of data manipulation within schemas.

```typescript
z.string().transform((val) => val.length);
```

--------------------------------

### Importing Zod v3 and v4 via Subpaths in TypeScript

Source: https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/blob/main/packages/docs/content/v4/versioning.mdx

This TypeScript code snippet illustrates how libraries can simultaneously import specific major versions of Zod (v3 and v4) using subpath imports. This method allows libraries to maintain compatibility with both versions, ensuring their implementations continue to work across major version bumps without requiring significant code changes or complex dependency management strategies.

```ts
import * as z3 from "zod/v3"
import * as z4 from "zod/v4"
```

--------------------------------

### Zod 3 Interleaving Transforms and Refinements

Source: https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/blob/main/packages/docs-v3/MIGRATION.md

This example showcases Zod 3's enhanced capability to interleave transformations and refinements within a single schema definition. Data flows sequentially through the chain of `.transform()` and `.refine()` calls, allowing for complex validation and manipulation logic. The final `.parse()` call executes the entire chain.

```typescript
const test = z
  .string()
  .transform((val) => val.length)
  .refine((val) => val > 5, { message: "Input is too short" })
  .transform((val) => val * 2);

test.parse("12characters"); // => 24
```

--------------------------------

### Chain Zod `.refine()` with other schema methods

Source: https://github.com/colinhacks/zod/blob/main/packages/docs/content/v4/index.mdx

Illustrates how Zod 4 allows `.refine()` to be chained directly with other schema methods like `.min()`, unlike Zod 3 where `ZodEffects` broke the chain. This change makes schema definition more fluid and intuitive, as refinements are now intrinsic to the schema.

```typescript
z.string()
  .refine(val => val.includes("@"))
  .min(5);
// ^ ❌ Property 'min' does not exist on type ZodEffects<ZodString, string, string>
```

```typescript
z.string()
  .refine(val => val.includes("@"))
  .min(5); // ✅
```

